{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17616899","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17616899"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:08:17+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:08:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16445"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16445","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16445"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9136"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74745"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9136","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9136"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16445"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60230"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"6"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1531"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"10378"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21701"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21702"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74745","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74745"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ECognition encompasses perception, memory, judgment, perceptual speed, spatial manipulation and reasoning.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following cognitive changes is typically associated with normal ageing?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Reduced processing speed","Increased verbal fluency","Better spatial reasoning","Improved attention span","Enhanced declarative memory"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ENormal cognitive ageing involves predictable changes in various domains of cognitive function. \u003Cstrong\u003EReduced processing speed\u003C/strong\u003E is one of the most consistently observed changes in normal ageing. This manifests as taking longer to complete cognitive tasks and slower reaction times, even when accuracy is preserved.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImproved attention span\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect - attention typically declines with age, particularly divided attention and the ability to filter out irrelevant information.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEnhanced declarative memory\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect - declarative memory (conscious recall of facts and events) typically shows more decline than procedural memory (unconscious memory of skills and procedures) in normal aging.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBetter spatial reasoning\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. Spatial reasoning peaks in early adulthood and gradually declines with age.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased verbal fluency\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect - while vocabulary may remain stable or even improve until late in life, verbal fluency (the ability to generate words quickly) typically declines with age.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt\u0027s important to note that these changes occur gradually and vary significantly between individuals. Factors such as education, physical activity, and cognitive engagement can influence the rate and extent of cognitive ageing. Sudden or severe cognitive decline is not part of normal ageing and should prompt evaluation for underlying pathology.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Processing speed and attention decline with normal ageing","Procedural memory is better preserved than declarative memory in normal ageing","Verbal and spatial reasoning abilities typically peak in early adulthood and gradually decline thereafter"],"references":["Schulz M, Mayer C, Schlemm E, Frey BM, Malherbe C, Petersen M, Gallinat J, K\u00fchn S, Fiehler J, Hanning U, Twerenbold R, Gerloff C, Cheng B, Thomalla G. Association of Age and Structural Brain Changes With Functional Connectivity and Executive Function in a Middle-Aged to Older Population-Based Cohort. Front Aging Neurosci. 2022 Feb 25;14:782738. doi: 10.3389/fnagi.2022.782738. PMID: 35283749; PMCID: PMC8916110.","McGinnis SM, Brickhouse M, Pascual B, Dickerson BC. Age-related changes in the thickness of cortical zones in humans. Brain Topogr. 2011 Oct;24(3-4):279-91. doi: 10.1007/s10548-011-0198-6. Epub 2011 Aug 14. PMID: 21842406; PMCID: PMC3600370.","Singh, V. (2024).\u00a0Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022).\u00a0The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60230"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16445"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60230","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60230"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-26T18:48:02+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-26T18:48:37+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9136"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74745"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"6","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/6"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc75","name":"Geriatrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description